SUMMARY:Buildpacks: Towards 1.0\, AI and Other Things - Aidan Delaney\, Bloomberg
DESCRIPTION:Cloud Native Buildpacks (CNB) effortlessly transform source code into container images\, making cloud-native development simpler for your organization. This session will explore two main threads: The Road to 1.0\, focusing on the critical milestone of achieving the stability and feature set necessary for widespread user adoption. We will detail how the 1.0 release will provide a rock-solid\, production-ready foundation for your applications\, clarify what this new level of stability means for end-users\, and outline the key technical components (like the Lifecycle\, Platform\, and Builder) that are driving this readiness. In addition\, we will cover the rapidly evolving integration of AI and Machine Learning into the Buildpacks ecosystem\, showcasing new features and experiments that simplify building and deploying AI-driven applications. Attendees will gain a clear understanding of the 1.0 goals for the core spec and implementation\, and learn the best ways to contribute to the project.
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:E106-108\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:3fab07331a79c8c51cfcaf6d9c45bd2d
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/3fab07331a79c8c51cfcaf6d9c45bd2d
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260326T133000Z
DTEND:20260326T140000Z
SUMMARY:CRI-O: Faster Pulls\, Better Metrics\, and a Future Beyond Images - Sohan Kunkerkar & Ayato Tokubi\, Red Hat
DESCRIPTION:CRI-O continues to evolve to support modern Kubernetes clusters in today’s AI-driven\, cloud-native environments. This session will cover ongoing and upcoming work\, including runtime metrics stabilization\, enhancements in OCI artifact and image volume support\, and experimentation in peer-to-peer image distribution. We will also highlight recent updates from SIG Node and security improvements. Additionally\, we will explore the future of CRI-O beyond P2P image distribution and traditional container images\, outlining the next steps for runtime innovation. Attendees will gain insights into the direction of CRI-O and the opportunities these developments create.
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:F002-005\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:10703557cb9b4b5ac874d694ad02b84c
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/10703557cb9b4b5ac874d694ad02b84c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260326T133000Z
DTEND:20260326T140000Z
SUMMARY:Envoy in the Era of Agentic Workloads - Yan Avlasov\, Google & Erica Hughberg\, Tetrate
DESCRIPTION:Agentic workloads have presented new challenges for the underlying network and require both the data and control planes to evolve. This talk presents Envoy and Envoy AI Gateway as building blocks for service-centric networking for Inference\, MCP\, and A2A requests. Providing you with a reliable and extensible foundation for your agentic systems. In this presentation\, you will get an overview of configuration APIs\, a deep dive into implementation details\, and the roadmap ahead\, directly from the maintainers.
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:G102-103\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:f52983fe92de9787b2788d1ec820d69d
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/f52983fe92de9787b2788d1ec820d69d
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260326T133000Z
DTEND:20260326T140000Z
SUMMARY:Harbor Project - The Maintainers Session - Yan Wang\, Broadcom & Vadim Bauer\, 8gears
DESCRIPTION:Harbor continues to evolve as a core cloud-native registry\, supporting secure and scalable software delivery across Kubernetes environments. In this maintainer update\, we’ll highlight key improvements from Harbor 2.14 and 2.15\, shaped by operator and community feedback. \n \n The session will cover notable enhancements in security\, registry operations\, and day-2 manageability\, along with important architectural and API changes relevant to platform teams\, integrators\, and contributors. We’ll also touch on how recent releases improve upgradeability\, performance\, and ecosystem integration. \n \n To close\, we’ll look ahead at what’s coming next for Harbor\, including upcoming roadmap items\, active design discussions\, and ways for the community to get involved. Attendees will leave with a clear view of where Harbor stands today and how they can help shape its future.
CATEGORIES:MAINTAINER TRACK
LOCATION:E103-105\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:42a1dcdd868720c82cc2c58e245df399
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/42a1dcdd868720c82cc2c58e245df399
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260326T133000Z
DTEND:20260326T140000Z
SUMMARY:Making Topology-Aware Scheduling Practical for AI Workloads: From Discovery to Simulation at Scale - Weizhou Lan\, Daocloud
DESCRIPTION:In large-scale AI inference clusters\, multi-tenant workloads require both efficient GPU utilization and dynamic RDMA networking. However\, heterogeneous GPU interconnect technologies inevitably lead to multi-level network topologies\, such as scale-up networks and RDMA spine–leaf structures.\nThese diverse topologies introduce several challenges: Dynamic topology discovery and health detection across multiple layers\, including scale-up\, RDMA spine\, and RDMA leaf. Second\, Topology-aware scheduling that supports priority-based placement and ensures GPUs leverage optimal communication paths.Third\, Validation at scale\, requiring cost-effective simulation of large\, multi-level topologies instead of relying on expensive hardware.\nIn this talk\, it will share practical approach of topology discovery to help Kueue to achieve topology-aware scheduling\, and showcase how Kwok simulates thousands of virtual nodes with multi-level topologies\, enabling large-scale validation at zero hardware cost.
CATEGORIES:OPERATIONS + PERFORMANCE
LOCATION:Hall 8 | Room D\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:b2804fb882af3d815d29f0ce7a944629
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/b2804fb882af3d815d29f0ce7a944629
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260326T133000Z
DTEND:20260326T140000Z
SUMMARY:Redefining SLIs for LLM Inference: Managing Hybrid Cloud with vLLM & LLM-D - Christopher Nuland & Hilliary Lipsig\, Red Hat
DESCRIPTION:Large Language Models (LLM) are reshaping application delivery\, introducing new operational challenges for SREs. Traditional metrics like CPU or request latency are no longer sufficient. Latency is now measured in tokens per second\, and reliability depends on routing efficiency and cache hit rates. In hybrid cloud environments\, inference pipelines span gateways\, schedulers\, caches\, and sharded backends\, complicating observability and SLO management. This session explores evolving SLOs/SLIs for production LLMs\, covering metrics like Time-to-First-Token (TTFT)\, cache hit ratio\, routing latency\, and GPU utilization. We’ll show how vLLM and llm-d provide the primitives for scalable\, observable inference: vLLM for high-performance batching and caching\, and llm-d for intelligent scheduling and KV-cache-aware routing. Attendees will learn to define new SLOs\, instrument distributed inference with Prometheus\, OpenTelemetry\, and Grafana\, and integrate LLM telemetry into Kubernetes SRE workflows.
CATEGORIES:OPERATIONS + PERFORMANCE
LOCATION:Hall 7 | Room A\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
SEQUENCE:0
UID:a664e9aa940f325224175075c945a0db
URL:http://kccnceu2026.sched.com/event/a664e9aa940f325224175075c945a0db
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20260317T131510Z
DTSTART:20260326T133000Z
DTEND:20260326T140000Z
SUMMARY:Freedom Through Boundaries: Building Configurations That Age Well - Bogdan Stancu\, Adobe
DESCRIPTION:Just a Helm Chart. It always starts simple. A few options\, a couple of flags\, and the best intentions. Then the requests start coming in. “Can we also support this?” “What if someone needs that?” Before long\, the config file looks like a museum of past decisions\, full of toggles nobody remembers adding and an ever-increasing queue of new feature requests.\n\nAfter maintaining one of those for too long\, I learned that flexibility is not about offering every possible switch. It is about choosing the right ones. Real freedom comes from clear boundaries\, good defaults\, and the courage to remove things that no longer make sense\, or just say no.\n\nWe will explore what happens when configuration grows too much\, how to make it healthy again\, and how to better communicate decisions to users.
CATEGORIES:PLATFORM ENGINEERING
LOCATION:Forum\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands
